    "body": "@aulphar I think that you are looking at why dictionaries don't do this by default? (which I think is what you want)\n\n```\nIn [7]: DataFrame.from_dict(d,orient='index')\nOut[7]: \n           0        1   2  3\nuser2  Logan  Howlett  33  M\nuser1   Jean     Grey  18  F\n```\n\nWell, numpy arrays are structured like:\n\n```\nIn [9]: arr = np.arange(6).reshape(3,2)\n\nIn [10]: arr\nOut[10]: \narray([[0, 1],\n       [2, 3],\n       [4, 5]])\n\nIn [11]: arr.shape\nOut[11]: (3, 2)\n\nIn [12]: DataFrame(arr)\nOut[12]: \n   0  1\n0  0  1\n1  2  3\n2  4  5\n```\n\nSo DataFrame closely follows this convention, where index is the 0th dimension, and columns is the next axis.\n\nHowever it is convinent to access a DataFrame by the columns, so df[0] in the case would give\n`Series([0,2,4])`\n\nits just a convention that has been in play for a long time. This is how columns are organized, while row-stored (e.g. SQL are primarily row-based), so I _would_ expect it to act differently.\n\nclosing as a usage question\n"
  },
